1
00:00:40,900 --> 00:00:42,340
Can I play?

2
00:00:42,460 --> 00:00:44,940
Do you have any marbles?

3
00:00:45,020 --> 00:00:46,580
Yep.

4
00:00:48,300 --> 00:00:49,820
OK.

5
00:00:49,900 --> 00:00:50,980
Thanks.

6
00:00:51,060 --> 00:00:52,460
You're welcome.

7
00:00:52,540 --> 00:00:53,820
So, what's your name?

8
00:00:53,900 --> 00:00:55,340
Louis. Yours?

9
00:00:55,420 --> 00:00:56,780
Alan.

10
00:00:56,820 --> 00:00:59,100
You're not from around here,
are you?

11
00:00:59,180 --> 00:01:02,500
No. I'm here with my parents
for the day.

12
00:01:07,540 --> 00:01:08,980
What?

13
00:01:09,100 --> 00:01:11,140
What's over there?

14
00:01:22,460 --> 00:01:24,660
Don't do that. We're not
even allowed to be here.

15
00:01:32,660 --> 00:01:34,180
Come on.

16
00:01:34,220 --> 00:01:35,820
Wait for me.

17
00:01:45,180 --> 00:01:47,300
Let's go back down.

18
00:01:47,380 --> 00:01:49,140
Nope.

19
00:01:50,540 --> 00:01:51,660
Don't!

20
00:02:04,380 --> 00:02:05,500
Alan, don't!

21
00:02:11,220 --> 00:02:13,300
See? That wasn't so bad.

22
00:02:13,380 --> 00:02:14,740
Just don't look down.

23
00:02:18,340 --> 00:02:19,500
Louis!

24
00:02:21,900 --> 00:02:23,460
Come on.

25
00:02:30,580 --> 00:02:32,900
See? It's steady.

26
00:02:52,020 --> 00:02:54,020
- Louis!
- I can't move!

27
00:02:54,100 --> 00:02:55,660
Come on!

28
00:02:57,580 --> 00:03:01,060
Alan, help!

29
00:03:03,420 --> 00:03:05,380
Wait!

30
00:06:29,940 --> 00:06:31,820
Here it comes. Just relax.

31
00:06:31,860 --> 00:06:33,380
You're doing great now.

32
00:06:33,460 --> 00:06:36,260
All right.
Now, just a couple more seconds.

33
00:06:36,340 --> 00:06:38,180
Here it comes, sweetie.

34
00:06:38,260 --> 00:06:39,940
Just keep breathing.

35
00:06:40,020 --> 00:06:42,660
All right, the head's crowning.
Very good.

36
00:06:42,740 --> 00:06:44,020
Excellent. Here we go.

37
00:06:44,100 --> 00:06:45,620
One more big push, sweetie.

38
00:06:45,700 --> 00:06:48,020
That's it. Now breathe.

39
00:06:48,100 --> 00:06:49,940
It's coming.

40
00:06:50,020 --> 00:06:52,420
Push, push, push!

41
00:06:54,820 --> 00:06:56,500
Oh, here we go.

42
00:06:56,620 --> 00:06:59,460
We have a boy.

43
00:07:02,060 --> 00:07:03,900
Oh, is he OK?

44
00:07:03,980 --> 00:07:06,340
- He's perfect.
- He's fine. He's fine.

45
00:07:06,380 --> 00:07:08,260
A beautiful son.

46
00:07:08,300 --> 00:07:11,180
Beautiful. He's beautiful.

47
00:07:17,260 --> 00:07:19,260
- Are we OK?
- He's fine, honey.

48
00:07:19,340 --> 00:07:21,740
- He's beautiful.
- Oh, he's perfect.

49
00:07:21,820 --> 00:07:24,380
Congratulations, Dad.

50
00:07:24,460 --> 00:07:26,145
Here he comes.

51
00:07:26,180 --> 00:07:28,060
You did really well.

52
00:07:28,100 --> 00:07:32,380
Oh, hi. Oh, it's OK.

53
00:07:32,420 --> 00:07:35,540
Beautiful baby boy.
You did really well.

54
00:07:35,620 --> 00:07:37,980
He's got his eyes open.
He's looking at you.

55
00:07:38,100 --> 00:07:40,860
- What's his name?
- Danny.

56
00:07:58,020 --> 00:07:59,740
Danny.

57
00:07:59,820 --> 00:08:02,740
Danny, come here, sweetie.
Get away from the ants.

58
00:08:06,540 --> 00:08:08,420
See, we have the best-fed ants
in the neighborhood.

59
00:08:08,500 --> 00:08:09,860
Come on.

60
00:08:09,940 --> 00:08:11,580
Have to do that later.

61
00:08:11,660 --> 00:08:13,860
Jason, my guys took
your guy's gun.

62
00:08:13,900 --> 00:08:16,060
Can't.
It's attached to his leg. See?

63
00:08:16,140 --> 00:08:17,700
Oh, my God.

64
00:08:17,740 --> 00:08:19,940
That's me, man.

65
00:08:21,420 --> 00:08:22,660
That's me.

66
00:08:22,740 --> 00:08:25,100
Danny, play nice
with your brother.

67
00:08:25,180 --> 00:08:28,100
What's that music you're using?
I really dig it.

68
00:08:31,820 --> 00:08:34,900
Whatever it is,
it's terrific, man.

69
00:08:35,020 --> 00:08:37,180
It really...

70
00:08:37,260 --> 00:08:39,540
I don't know...

71
00:08:39,620 --> 00:08:41,820
suits his life somehow.

72
00:08:41,860 --> 00:08:44,300
So, Danny, you still drawing?

73
00:08:44,380 --> 00:08:45,460
Nope.

74
00:08:45,540 --> 00:08:48,940
No? Didn't you want to grow up
to be an artist?

75
00:08:51,300 --> 00:08:52,820
That's some
of the opening sequence.

76
00:08:52,900 --> 00:08:55,580
The rest needs
some fixes and tweaks.

77
00:08:55,660 --> 00:08:58,140
But right now, he's clocking in
at one hour and 40 minutes.

78
00:08:58,220 --> 00:09:00,060
Yeah, that's cool.

79
00:09:01,380 --> 00:09:03,580
I just wanted to have a look...

80
00:09:03,620 --> 00:09:05,140
before the Rememory tomorrow.

81
00:09:05,220 --> 00:09:06,700
You know.

82
00:09:06,820 --> 00:09:08,820
You've done a hell of a job
with him, Mr. Hakman.

83
00:09:08,940 --> 00:09:10,780
You've done
the son of a bitch right.

84
00:09:10,860 --> 00:09:12,380
You're welcome.

85
00:09:14,820 --> 00:09:16,620
I don't suppose...

86
00:09:16,700 --> 00:09:18,940
There was a fishing trip
when we were 13.

87
00:09:19,020 --> 00:09:20,500
Just Danny and I and Dad...

88
00:09:20,580 --> 00:09:22,740
- At the cape.
- Yes, that one.

89
00:09:22,780 --> 00:09:25,060
My God,
that day is still with me.

90
00:09:25,100 --> 00:09:27,380
You requested it specifically.
It's there.

91
00:09:27,420 --> 00:09:29,820
Well, I'll be off, then.

92
00:09:42,580 --> 00:09:45,780
Closing Zoe project
D. Monroe, rough cut 6.

93
00:09:48,820 --> 00:09:52,500
Opening D. Monroe, scene 127-Q.

94
00:09:52,580 --> 00:09:54,060
Jesus Christ!

95
00:09:54,140 --> 00:09:56,620
I told you to shut up!

96
00:09:56,700 --> 00:09:59,660
Danny! Danny, stop!

97
00:09:59,740 --> 00:10:02,060
You...

98
00:10:02,140 --> 00:10:05,260
You deserve this, bitch!

99
00:10:05,340 --> 00:10:06,780
No!

100
00:10:06,860 --> 00:10:10,060
No! God! Please... please...

101
00:10:10,140 --> 00:10:13,500
No! Stop! No! You're killing me!

102
00:10:14,780 --> 00:10:15,900
Stop!

103
00:10:18,700 --> 00:10:21,780
Scene 127-Q deleted.

104
00:10:31,740 --> 00:10:33,700
EYE Tech introduces...

105
00:10:33,780 --> 00:10:36,100
the ninth generation
of the Zoe implant...

106
00:10:36,180 --> 00:10:38,380
from our family to yours.

107
00:10:38,420 --> 00:10:40,460
Do you think
we'll be able to afford one?

108
00:10:40,540 --> 00:10:42,340
Yep.

109
00:10:42,460 --> 00:10:43,700
I hope so.

110
00:10:43,780 --> 00:10:48,100
Well, we can save.
It's worth it, I think.

111
00:11:05,340 --> 00:11:07,060
Excuse me.

112
00:11:35,060 --> 00:11:38,300
This girl was a complete wreck.

113
00:11:38,380 --> 00:11:41,220
Drinking, drugs,
in and out of schools.

114
00:11:41,300 --> 00:11:42,580
Then she turns 21...

115
00:11:42,660 --> 00:11:45,540
and she finds out
about her Zoe implant.

116
00:11:45,620 --> 00:11:47,980
Complete 180. She's born again.

117
00:11:48,060 --> 00:11:50,860
Her knowing that
someone would one day watch...

118
00:11:50,940 --> 00:11:55,180
transforms her into this kind,
gentle, loving person.

119
00:11:55,220 --> 00:11:57,260
So, what happened?

120
00:11:57,340 --> 00:11:59,020
She committed suicide.

121
00:11:59,060 --> 00:12:01,100
Took a dive off her balcony...

122
00:12:01,180 --> 00:12:04,980
twenty-seven floors
straight onto her head.

123
00:12:05,060 --> 00:12:06,740
The implant
was instantly vaporized.

124
00:12:06,820 --> 00:12:09,500
Charming story, Hasan.
Please do go on.

125
00:12:09,580 --> 00:12:12,140
Alan!
This is a rare treat.

126
00:12:12,180 --> 00:12:13,540
Alan!

127
00:12:13,580 --> 00:12:15,900
Michael, this is Alan Hakman.

128
00:12:15,980 --> 00:12:17,060
- Hi.
- Hi.

129
00:12:17,180 --> 00:12:18,660
It's an honor to meet you.

130
00:12:18,780 --> 00:12:20,460
Mike is my new assistant.

131
00:12:20,580 --> 00:12:21,780
What happened to Eddie?

132
00:12:21,860 --> 00:12:24,500
Eddie freaked out on me.
Strung too tight.

133
00:12:24,540 --> 00:12:27,020
Hey, Alan, have you seen these?

134
00:12:27,100 --> 00:12:28,820
They are all over town.

135
00:12:28,900 --> 00:12:32,220
These anti-Zoe hippies always
seemed a little crazy to me.

136
00:12:32,300 --> 00:12:36,020
But now they just seem crazy.

137
00:12:36,100 --> 00:12:38,180
Listen...

138
00:12:38,220 --> 00:12:41,820
"It is not our place to see
through other people's eyes.

139
00:12:41,900 --> 00:12:45,980
"That is for God and God alone."

140
00:12:46,060 --> 00:12:48,980
Anyway, how's
the Monroe project coming?

141
00:12:49,060 --> 00:12:50,220
Fine.

142
00:12:50,300 --> 00:12:52,820
- Just fine?
- Just fine.

143
00:12:52,900 --> 00:12:55,500
Michael,
it's your great privilege...

144
00:12:55,580 --> 00:12:56,740
to meet this man.

145
00:12:56,780 --> 00:12:58,100
He's the best cutter in town.

146
00:12:58,180 --> 00:13:00,460
- Who's your assistant?
- I don't have an assistant.

147
00:13:00,540 --> 00:13:03,340
I have a friend that's looking
to get into the racket.

148
00:13:03,380 --> 00:13:05,460
I don't work with an assistant.

149
00:13:06,460 --> 00:13:08,020
You have
something for me, Thelma?

150
00:13:08,060 --> 00:13:09,260
Straight to business.

151
00:13:09,340 --> 00:13:12,140
I got a job last week
that I passed on...

152
00:13:12,180 --> 00:13:13,900
and I think
it's right up your alley.

153
00:13:13,940 --> 00:13:15,620
You know Charles Bannister?

154
00:13:15,700 --> 00:13:17,940
His widow
is looking for a cutter.

155
00:13:17,980 --> 00:13:19,220
Bannister, the EYE Tech lawyer?

156
00:13:19,260 --> 00:13:21,980
He was out jogging
and his heart collapsed.

157
00:13:22,060 --> 00:13:24,020
Wait a minute.
EYE Tech let that footage out?

158
00:13:24,140 --> 00:13:26,300
Jennifer Bannister
won the lawsuit against them...

159
00:13:26,380 --> 00:13:28,180
and claimed
her husband's implant.

160
00:13:28,260 --> 00:13:30,020
She insisted on having
her own cutter, too.

161
00:13:30,100 --> 00:13:31,900
And with good reason.

162
00:13:31,980 --> 00:13:33,380
We could have taken that job.

163
00:13:33,420 --> 00:13:35,020
After Caldwell,
our schedule is wide open.

164
00:13:35,100 --> 00:13:37,020
I don't like the ugly stuff.

165
00:13:37,060 --> 00:13:38,340
It gives me nightmares.

166
00:13:38,420 --> 00:13:41,060
And this pig Bannister...

167
00:13:41,140 --> 00:13:44,220
he's human garbage.

168
00:13:44,300 --> 00:13:47,940
I took one look at the footage
and sent it straight back.

169
00:13:48,020 --> 00:13:52,140
She only hired me because
you were busy with Monroe.

170
00:13:52,220 --> 00:13:53,780
It's you she really wants.

171
00:13:53,900 --> 00:13:55,740
- I'm available.
- Good.

172
00:13:55,780 --> 00:13:57,060
Our friend Alan...

173
00:13:57,140 --> 00:13:59,060
that's his specialty,
so to speak.

174
00:13:59,180 --> 00:14:01,900
If you can't bear
to look at it, he will.

175
00:14:01,980 --> 00:14:03,660
I'll tell her
you'll come by tomorrow.

176
00:14:03,700 --> 00:14:05,140
She'll be expecting you.

177
00:14:07,540 --> 00:14:08,900
We should actually go.

178
00:14:08,980 --> 00:14:10,700
Oh, yes.
Rememory is in two days...

179
00:14:10,780 --> 00:14:12,620
and we're still cutting picture.

180
00:14:12,660 --> 00:14:14,500
Goddamn last-minute jobs.

181
00:14:14,580 --> 00:14:16,980
Thelma, come on.
It keeps you young.

182
00:14:17,020 --> 00:14:18,740
Alan.

183
00:14:20,340 --> 00:14:21,740
Hasan.

184
00:14:21,820 --> 00:14:25,260
Oh, hey, Alan.
I've been working on...

185
00:14:25,340 --> 00:14:27,380
this new sorting program
for the Guillotine...

186
00:14:27,460 --> 00:14:30,340
and I would really love
to get your feedback on it.

187
00:14:30,420 --> 00:14:31,860
Maybe another time.

188
00:14:35,060 --> 00:14:37,260
Yeah, maybe some other time.

189
00:14:54,900 --> 00:14:56,780
Put it in archives very gently.

190
00:14:56,860 --> 00:14:58,020
- Sure.
- All right.

191
00:14:58,140 --> 00:15:00,580
Delila,
is suicide under self-help?

192
00:15:02,580 --> 00:15:03,860
What are you doing here?

193
00:15:03,940 --> 00:15:06,620
I just wanted to talk.

194
00:15:08,020 --> 00:15:09,460
I'm busy.

195
00:15:12,540 --> 00:15:15,660
Store's still open.
It's the 11:30 rush.

196
00:15:15,700 --> 00:15:17,940
Books are flying off the shelf.

197
00:15:23,980 --> 00:15:26,340
We close in 20 minutes.

198
00:15:35,180 --> 00:15:37,020
This is exciting.

199
00:15:37,100 --> 00:15:38,500
You've never had me over before.

200
00:15:38,580 --> 00:15:40,420
You've always
wanted to see my work.

201
00:15:40,500 --> 00:15:42,180
Well, you're always working.

202
00:15:42,260 --> 00:15:45,260
I'm curious about
what takes up all your time.

203
00:16:31,820 --> 00:16:33,540
Guillotine.

204
00:16:36,660 --> 00:16:39,460
You're like a mortician...

205
00:16:39,540 --> 00:16:41,100
or a priest...

206
00:16:42,540 --> 00:16:44,260
or a taxidermist.

207
00:16:44,340 --> 00:16:45,900
All of them.

208
00:16:47,580 --> 00:16:49,540
I mean...

209
00:16:50,900 --> 00:16:53,380
you get to see life upon life.

210
00:16:53,460 --> 00:16:56,460
Most of us get only one,
if that.

211
00:16:57,980 --> 00:16:59,620
What are people's lives like?

212
00:16:59,700 --> 00:17:02,140
Do they make any sense?

213
00:17:02,180 --> 00:17:05,100
It all seems so massive
and so random.

214
00:17:05,180 --> 00:17:08,140
Have you ever been
to a Rememory?

215
00:17:08,220 --> 00:17:11,300
No. Well...

216
00:17:11,380 --> 00:17:13,100
Once, a few years ago.

217
00:17:13,180 --> 00:17:14,380
Whose?

218
00:17:16,140 --> 00:17:18,700
My ex-boyfriend.

219
00:17:18,780 --> 00:17:21,820
But I couldn't take it.
I didn't stay.

220
00:17:21,860 --> 00:17:23,260
Why not?

221
00:17:24,620 --> 00:17:26,500
Because it just wasn't...

222
00:17:28,140 --> 00:17:30,180
It wasn't him.

223
00:17:31,660 --> 00:17:34,500
And I wanted
to remember him my way.

224
00:17:35,980 --> 00:17:38,060
Sit down.

225
00:17:43,140 --> 00:17:44,580
Thank you.

226
00:18:37,700 --> 00:18:40,620
It's like
you read my mind, Alan.

227
00:18:40,700 --> 00:18:44,260
I have this recurring dream
where I'm aging backwards.

228
00:19:18,900 --> 00:19:20,540
Wow.

229
00:19:26,420 --> 00:19:28,620
What about all the bits
in between?

230
00:19:28,660 --> 00:19:30,060
It's a miniature.

231
00:19:30,140 --> 00:19:32,700
Concise, symmetrical.

232
00:19:32,740 --> 00:19:35,020
That's the way the world
looks to me...

233
00:19:35,060 --> 00:19:36,420
the way I see it.

234
00:19:37,660 --> 00:19:40,100
How do you do this?

235
00:19:40,180 --> 00:19:42,900
It's what I was meant to do.

236
00:19:42,940 --> 00:19:46,860
You were meant
to live your own life, too.

237
00:19:52,900 --> 00:19:54,780
- Hey.
- Hey.

238
00:20:09,140 --> 00:20:10,940
The house was big...

239
00:20:11,020 --> 00:20:13,380
enormous...

240
00:20:13,460 --> 00:20:15,180
like this one.

241
00:20:15,260 --> 00:20:17,700
We didn't care
whose house it was.

242
00:20:17,820 --> 00:20:21,820
It felt dangerous to be there.

243
00:20:21,900 --> 00:20:25,140
It felt exciting.

244
00:20:25,220 --> 00:20:27,500
I can see the grass.

245
00:20:27,540 --> 00:20:31,020
I can hear it
crunching beneath our feet.

246
00:20:31,100 --> 00:20:32,980
And then the sprinklers
came on...

247
00:20:33,060 --> 00:20:35,340
all around us...

248
00:20:35,420 --> 00:20:37,460
and we ran.

249
00:20:38,980 --> 00:20:41,780
I remember that
like it was yesterday.

250
00:20:45,460 --> 00:20:48,780
Do you recall any moments
with your daughter?

251
00:20:50,860 --> 00:20:53,340
This isn't long ago.

252
00:20:53,420 --> 00:20:56,260
We were watching Isabel
in a school talent show.

253
00:20:56,300 --> 00:20:59,420
She was wonderful that night.

254
00:20:59,500 --> 00:21:02,780
I think Charles and I
both felt...

255
00:21:02,860 --> 00:21:05,620
what an amazing thing
a family was.

256
00:21:05,660 --> 00:21:07,620
We felt it together.

257
00:21:09,140 --> 00:21:11,820
She was up there on that stage.

258
00:21:13,900 --> 00:21:16,900
Oh, goodness.

259
00:21:18,580 --> 00:21:20,140
Excuse me.

260
00:21:20,180 --> 00:21:22,820
I know this is very hard,
Mrs. Bannister...

261
00:21:22,900 --> 00:21:24,580
but it's important.

262
00:21:24,660 --> 00:21:27,140
It's the foundation
of a cutter's work.

263
00:21:27,220 --> 00:21:29,060
I need you and your family...

264
00:21:29,140 --> 00:21:31,900
to help me choose
those moments you want to keep.

265
00:21:33,140 --> 00:21:35,020
I won't be able to do
your husband justice...

266
00:21:35,060 --> 00:21:37,940
if I don't understand him
through you.

267
00:21:40,260 --> 00:21:42,860
I heard you were the best...

268
00:21:42,940 --> 00:21:46,340
that you would know
how to handle Charles.

269
00:21:48,020 --> 00:21:52,220
My husband was a great man,
Mr. Hakman.

270
00:21:52,260 --> 00:21:55,420
He deserves to be remembered
as a great man.

271
00:21:55,500 --> 00:21:56,620
After my initial cut...

