00:41:06,460 --> 00:41:08,260
What happened to him
after he quit?

544
00:41:08,340 --> 00:41:10,180
He seems changed.

545
00:41:10,260 --> 00:41:13,100
We kept in touch
for a few years...

546
00:41:13,140 --> 00:41:15,980
and then his sister Laura...
You remember Laura.

547
00:41:16,020 --> 00:41:18,780
She had a son,
died of leukemia.

548
00:41:18,860 --> 00:41:22,620
He was only twelve.
She never got over it.

549
00:41:22,700 --> 00:41:27,140
She spent days and days watching
his unedited Zoe footage...

550
00:41:27,180 --> 00:41:30,020
stopped speaking to everyone.

551
00:41:30,100 --> 00:41:33,500
And then she didn't even
recognize who Fletcher was.

552
00:41:33,540 --> 00:41:36,580
After that, he dropped off
the map completely.

553
00:41:36,660 --> 00:41:39,060
Think he could be involved
with anti-implant groups?

554
00:41:39,100 --> 00:41:40,900
I've heard rumors...

555
00:41:40,980 --> 00:41:43,900
talk of them being organized
by an ex-cutter.

556
00:41:43,980 --> 00:41:46,300
I never thought
it could be Fletcher.

557
00:41:46,340 --> 00:41:50,100
He wants to buy
Bannister's footage.

558
00:41:50,340 --> 00:41:55,140
These anti-implant groups have
become like religious fanatics.

559
00:41:55,220 --> 00:41:59,140
They gave Michael one hell
of a beating last night.

560
00:41:59,220 --> 00:42:02,860
So it's not just talk anymore.

561
00:42:02,940 --> 00:42:05,620
You know,
if they want Bannister's life...

562
00:42:05,700 --> 00:42:07,580
the bastard's
not worth fighting for.

563
00:42:07,660 --> 00:42:08,820
Give the footage
back to his widow.

564
00:42:08,900 --> 00:42:10,020
Let her deal with it.

565
00:42:10,060 --> 00:42:11,500
I can't give it back.

566
00:42:11,580 --> 00:42:13,220
There's someone in that project
I haven't seen for years.

567
00:42:13,300 --> 00:42:14,660
I hate when that happens.

568
00:42:14,700 --> 00:42:16,545
Oh, yeah.

569
00:42:16,580 --> 00:42:18,300
He's at a party, in a crowd...

570
00:42:18,380 --> 00:42:20,260
never mentioned by name.

571
00:42:20,300 --> 00:42:22,145
I've got to find him, though.

572
00:42:22,180 --> 00:42:24,540
He's not a main character
in Bannister's life.

573
00:42:24,620 --> 00:42:25,980
It'll take
the Guillotine days...

574
00:42:26,020 --> 00:42:27,820
to track his face
through the footage.

575
00:42:27,860 --> 00:42:29,500
Who is this person?

576
00:42:31,820 --> 00:42:33,980
Just someone from my childhood.

577
00:42:34,060 --> 00:42:36,420
Bannister's life
is my only lead.

578
00:42:39,820 --> 00:42:43,660
OK. Go through the family,
snoop around...

579
00:42:43,740 --> 00:42:46,740
tell them you're doing research
for the project.

580
00:42:46,860 --> 00:42:50,180
It might be faster
than waiting for the Guillotine.

581
00:42:51,700 --> 00:42:54,020
Be careful, Alan.

582
00:43:08,100 --> 00:43:10,100
So...

583
00:43:10,180 --> 00:43:12,060
how is it that you and I
know each other again?

584
00:43:12,140 --> 00:43:13,700
We don't.

585
00:43:13,780 --> 00:43:16,220
That's the wrong answer, pal.

586
00:43:16,340 --> 00:43:18,900
We share a mutual friend.
Billy Finch.

587
00:43:18,980 --> 00:43:20,980
Billy who?

588
00:43:21,100 --> 00:43:22,780
Don't play games.
I know you better than that.

589
00:43:22,860 --> 00:43:24,860
I know all
your little secrets, Oliver.

590
00:43:24,940 --> 00:43:26,140
How do you know my name?

591
00:43:26,220 --> 00:43:29,380
I know that you suffocated
those kittens when you were 13.

592
00:43:29,460 --> 00:43:32,060
I know that that scar on
your head was self-inflicted...

593
00:43:32,140 --> 00:43:33,500
and I know
that you sold Billy the gun...

594
00:43:33,580 --> 00:43:35,580
that he killed his brother with.

595
00:43:35,660 --> 00:43:37,500
They say that friends
help you move...

596
00:43:37,580 --> 00:43:40,220
but good friends help you
move bodies, don't they?

597
00:43:40,300 --> 00:43:42,660
I just want what Billy wanted.

598
00:43:42,700 --> 00:43:44,180
A gun.

599
00:43:50,100 --> 00:43:51,620
Take it. Take it.

600
00:43:55,380 --> 00:43:57,380
And these. Take these.

601
00:43:57,460 --> 00:43:59,580
Take them all.

602
00:43:59,620 --> 00:44:02,380
Please go, OK? Just go.

603
00:44:02,420 --> 00:44:04,940
Thank you, Ollie.

604
00:44:06,220 --> 00:44:07,780
Take care.

605
00:44:24,660 --> 00:44:26,300
I'm here.

606
00:44:26,380 --> 00:44:28,540
Is this why you wanted
to meet me here?

607
00:44:28,580 --> 00:44:30,180
I thought
it would be safer this way.

608
00:44:31,940 --> 00:44:33,180
How's Thelma doing?

609
00:44:33,260 --> 00:44:37,060
I can't give you Bannister,
and you know I can't.

610
00:44:37,095 --> 00:44:39,620
It's unbelievable,
when you think about it.

611
00:44:41,100 --> 00:44:43,620
One in twenty of these people
has an implant.

612
00:44:43,700 --> 00:44:47,100
How will that baby remember
his mother years from now?

613
00:44:47,180 --> 00:44:49,660
Will he remember the special
moments between them...

614
00:44:49,780 --> 00:44:53,660
or moments someone like you
decides are special?

615
00:44:53,780 --> 00:44:55,180
My job is
to help people remember...

616
00:44:55,220 --> 00:44:57,180
what they want to remember,
Fletcher.

617
00:44:57,300 --> 00:45:00,100
Ah. Oh, that's noble.

618
00:45:00,180 --> 00:45:03,060
But I don't think you understand
the scope of the damage.

619
00:45:03,140 --> 00:45:04,460
There is no way to measure...

620
00:45:04,500 --> 00:45:06,660
the profound effect
the Zoe implant has had...

621
00:45:06,740 --> 00:45:08,660
on the way
people relate to each other.

622
00:45:08,740 --> 00:45:11,580
"Am I being filmed?
Should I say this or not?

623
00:45:11,620 --> 00:45:14,700
"What'll they think in 30 years
if I do this or that?"

624
00:45:14,780 --> 00:45:17,500
What about the simple right
not to be photographed?

625
00:45:17,580 --> 00:45:19,380
The right not to pop up
in some guy's Rememory...

626
00:45:19,460 --> 00:45:21,300
without even knowing
you were being filmed?

627
00:45:21,420 --> 00:45:22,940
I didn't invent the technology.

628
00:45:22,980 --> 00:45:25,340
If people didn't want it,
they wouldn't buy it, Fletcher.

629
00:45:25,420 --> 00:45:26,980
It fulfills a human need.

630
00:45:27,060 --> 00:45:29,940
Alan, you take murderers
and make them saints.

631
00:45:29,980 --> 00:45:32,260
That's why we need
Charles Bannister.

632
00:45:32,340 --> 00:45:33,660
He was a public figure
for EYE Tech...

633
00:45:33,740 --> 00:45:35,105
their star attorney...

634
00:45:35,140 --> 00:45:36,540
well respected,
loved his family...

635
00:45:36,620 --> 00:45:38,660
gave to charity, and if
you get through with him...

636
00:45:38,740 --> 00:45:40,860
that's all
anyone will ever know.

637
00:45:40,940 --> 00:45:43,380
But Bannister is
the first EYE Tech employee...

638
00:45:43,460 --> 00:45:45,660
whose implant has left
the confines of the corporation.

639
00:45:45,740 --> 00:45:47,260
His widow fought for that.

640
00:45:47,300 --> 00:45:50,340
We know she's hiding something
about him and his daughter...

641
00:45:50,380 --> 00:45:51,860
and we're gonna find it.

642
00:45:51,940 --> 00:45:53,460
EYE Tech's hands aren't clean.

643
00:45:53,580 --> 00:45:55,180
Bannister's implant is evidence.

644
00:45:55,260 --> 00:45:56,860
So you want to destroy
EYE Tech with a scandal?

645
00:45:56,940 --> 00:45:59,740
Absolutely.
The press would go apeshit.

646
00:45:59,820 --> 00:46:01,060
He's the perfect candidate.

647
00:46:01,140 --> 00:46:02,940
I must have his footage.

648
00:46:06,020 --> 00:46:08,220
Is this about your sister?

649
00:46:10,180 --> 00:46:12,020
Don't even say her name.

650
00:46:12,100 --> 00:46:14,460
You don't know anything
about that.

651
00:46:16,740 --> 00:46:19,105
She has nothing to do with it.

652
00:46:19,140 --> 00:46:21,820
These implants
distort personal history...

653
00:46:21,860 --> 00:46:23,740
and therefore all history...

654
00:46:23,820 --> 00:46:26,460
and I will not stand by
while the past is rewritten...

655
00:46:26,540 --> 00:46:28,180
for the sake
of pleasant Rememories.

656
00:46:28,300 --> 00:46:29,540
Tell me something.

657
00:46:29,620 --> 00:46:31,460
Why is your name
the first on the list...

658
00:46:31,540 --> 00:46:32,980
for cutting
scumbags and lowlifes?

659
00:46:33,100 --> 00:46:34,980
Because I forgive people
long after...

660
00:46:35,060 --> 00:46:36,700
they could be punished
for their sins.

661
00:46:36,780 --> 00:46:39,300
I know what you do.

662
00:46:39,380 --> 00:46:41,660
Why do you do it?

663
00:46:41,700 --> 00:46:44,260
Do you know
what a sin eater is?

664
00:46:47,300 --> 00:46:50,740
It's part of
an ancient tradition.

665
00:46:50,820 --> 00:46:54,140
When someone would die,
they would call for a sin eater.

666
00:46:54,220 --> 00:46:57,820
Sin eaters were
social outcasts, marginals.

667
00:46:57,940 --> 00:46:59,100
They would lay out the body...

668
00:46:59,220 --> 00:47:01,300
put bread and salt
on the chest...

669
00:47:01,380 --> 00:47:03,100
coins upon the eyes.

670
00:47:03,180 --> 00:47:05,300
The sin eater would eat
the bread and salt...

671
00:47:05,380 --> 00:47:07,220
take the coins as payment.

672
00:47:07,300 --> 00:47:10,100
By doing this,
the eater absorbed...

673
00:47:10,180 --> 00:47:12,860
the sins of the deceased,
cleansing their soul...

674
00:47:12,940 --> 00:47:16,060
and allowing them safe passage
into the afterlife.

675
00:47:16,140 --> 00:47:17,780
That was their job.

676
00:47:22,020 --> 00:47:23,540
And what about the sin eater...

677
00:47:23,620 --> 00:47:26,580
who bears the burden
of all those wrongs?

678
00:47:26,660 --> 00:47:29,380
Are you worried
about my soul, Fletcher?

679
00:47:32,940 --> 00:47:34,500
I will have Bannister.

680
00:47:34,620 --> 00:47:36,980
I can't give him to you.

681
00:47:39,340 --> 00:47:42,020
You see that man behind me?

682
00:47:42,100 --> 00:47:45,620
I don't want to bring him
into this conversation...

683
00:47:45,700 --> 00:47:49,700
but I will if you leave me
no other choice.

684
00:47:49,780 --> 00:47:51,180
Alan!

685
00:47:52,300 --> 00:47:53,540
Alan!

686
00:48:16,860 --> 00:48:18,060
Do you remember the moment...

687
00:48:18,100 --> 00:48:19,980
you first fell in love
with your husband?

688
00:48:22,300 --> 00:48:26,460
Goodness. How can you answer
a question like that?

689
00:48:26,540 --> 00:48:27,425
The pier?

690
00:48:27,460 --> 00:48:28,940
Yes, the pier.

691
00:48:29,020 --> 00:48:31,420
He had taken me down
to the pier.

692
00:48:31,500 --> 00:48:33,060
It was springtime.

693
00:48:33,180 --> 00:48:34,980
We were walking,
and he was going on...

694
00:48:35,060 --> 00:48:36,460
This was during college?

695
00:48:36,540 --> 00:48:38,020
Yes, I was in college...

696
00:48:38,100 --> 00:48:39,940
and I remember,
I looked up at him...

697
00:48:40,020 --> 00:48:41,540
and I thought,
this is the man...

698
00:48:41,620 --> 00:48:43,700
I want to spend
the rest of my life with.

699
00:48:45,460 --> 00:48:47,340
I just have one more question.

700
00:48:47,380 --> 00:48:49,580
There was a man
at one of your parties.

701
00:48:49,660 --> 00:48:51,660
- A man?
- Yes. A man with glasses.

702
00:48:51,740 --> 00:48:53,860
You may have noticed them.
They're very thick glasses.

703
00:48:53,900 --> 00:48:55,420
Thick glasses?

704
00:48:55,460 --> 00:48:58,580
Mr. Hakman,
how is this relevant?

705
00:48:58,660 --> 00:49:01,540
Minor people I don't even know
have no place in the Rememory.

706
00:49:01,620 --> 00:49:03,420
Family...

707
00:49:03,500 --> 00:49:05,020
career...

708
00:49:05,100 --> 00:49:06,620
community.

709
00:49:06,740 --> 00:49:10,020
That's all I want.
Cut everything else.

710
00:49:11,420 --> 00:49:13,540
Maybe I could speak with Isabel?

711
00:49:14,900 --> 00:49:16,300
Right now?

712
00:49:16,380 --> 00:49:17,900
It would be very helpful.

713
00:49:20,140 --> 00:49:22,340
Yes, of course.

714
00:49:25,420 --> 00:49:26,500
Isabel?

715
00:49:29,780 --> 00:49:32,780
Remember what I told you?

716
00:49:32,860 --> 00:49:35,500
Mr. Hakman wants
to talk to you about Daddy.

717
00:49:35,580 --> 00:49:37,540
It's for Daddy's Rememory.

718
00:49:37,660 --> 00:49:38,700
Mrs. Bannister?

719
00:49:38,820 --> 00:49:40,940
We have a problem
with the caterers.

720
00:49:49,060 --> 00:49:50,740
Hi, Isabel.

721
00:49:50,820 --> 00:49:52,700
Hello, Mr. Hakman.

722
00:49:52,780 --> 00:49:54,940
"Mr. Hakman."
That's very formal.

723
00:49:55,020 --> 00:49:57,700
My name is Alan.

724
00:49:57,780 --> 00:50:00,700
Beautiful house.
What's going on in there?

725
00:50:00,780 --> 00:50:03,100
Birthday party for Mr. Froggy.

726
00:50:03,180 --> 00:50:04,540
Do you think Mr. Froggy
would mind...

727
00:50:04,580 --> 00:50:06,460
if I took you away
from the party for a minute?

728
00:50:06,500 --> 00:50:08,260
OK.

729
00:50:22,260 --> 00:50:24,100
Who's that in your arms?

730
00:50:24,180 --> 00:50:25,700
My doll.

731
00:50:25,740 --> 00:50:28,020
Oh. What's her name?

732
00:50:28,100 --> 00:50:31,860
She doesn't have a name.
She's just a doll. See?

733
00:50:35,820 --> 00:50:37,940
Isabel, your daddy...

734
00:50:38,020 --> 00:50:39,980
My daddy is the best daddy
in the world.

735
00:50:40,060 --> 00:50:42,340
He had a really big meeting
one day...

736
00:50:42,420 --> 00:50:44,300
but instead,
he took me horseback riding.

737
00:50:44,380 --> 00:50:47,260
He would read me stories
before bed every night.

738
00:50:47,380 --> 00:50:49,980
Sometimes he would make it up
as he went along...

739
00:50:50,060 --> 00:50:52,620
and I knew, but I didn't care.

740
00:50:54,380 --> 00:50:57,820
Your mom said I was here
to talk about your dad.

741
00:50:57,900 --> 00:51:00,220
But we don't have to do that
if you don't want.

742
00:51:00,300 --> 00:51:02,300
I don't want.

743
00:51:02,380 --> 00:51:06,020
OK. Then we won't.

744
00:51:10,780 --> 00:51:13,020
When I was a little older
than you...

745
00:51:13,140 --> 00:51:15,300
I lost both my parents.

746
00:51:16,820 --> 00:51:18,980
Not many people
know what you're feeling.

747
00:51:19,020 --> 00:51:21,500
Not many people understand.

748
00:51:21,620 --> 00:51:23,180
But I do.

749
00:51:24,900 --> 00:51:28,420
You don't want me nosing around,
asking questions.

750
00:51:28,500 --> 00:51:30,380
And you're right.

751
00:51:33,900 --> 00:51:35,180
OK.

752
00:51:37,140 --> 00:51:38,740
Alan...

753
00:51:38,820 --> 00:51:42,340
it's not really
Mr. Froggy's birthday.

754
00:51:43,860 --> 00:51:45,580
It's in a week.

755
00:51:49,100 --> 00:51:51,780
Can I ask one question?
And then I'm gone.

756
00:51:53,100 --> 00:51:56,380
There was a man at
one of your parents' parties.

757
00:51:56,460 --> 00:51:58,300
The thing that's special
about this man...

758
00:51:58,380 --> 00:52:01,020
is he wore glasses
that were very, very thick.

759
00:52:01,060 --> 00:52:03,900
They're almost like the bottom
of a glass bottle.

760
00:52:03,980 --> 00:52:07,420
Mr. Hunt.
I took him the invitation.

761
00:52:07,500 --> 00:52:09,020
Mr. Hunt?

762
00:52:09,100 --> 00:52:11,460
Was his name Louis Hunt?

763
00:52:11,500 --> 00:52:13,020
He was my teacher.

764
00:52:13,100 --> 00:52:15,420
Really? What does he teach?

765
00:52:15,500 --> 00:52:18,260
He doesn't teach anymore.

766
00:52:18,340 --> 00:52:21,940
He died in a car accident
a year ago.

767
00:52:22,020 --> 00:52:23,300
It was very sad.

768
00:52:23,380 --> 00:52:25,700
Did you have a Rememory,
like for your father?

769
00:52:25,780 --> 00:52:27,020
I don't know.

770
00:52:27,100 --> 00:52:28,980
We just had a day at school
where we talked about him.

771
00:52:32,500 --> 00:52:34,340
Thank you, Isabel.

772
00:52:37,940 --> 00:52:39,060
Alan?

773
00:52:41,580 --> 00:52:44,620
Are you gonna fix
what my daddy can remember?

774
00:52:48,100 --> 00:52:50,220
In a way... yes.

775
00:52:51,500 --> 00:52:54,460
Can you make him forget
that I...

776
00:52:54,580 --> 00:52:57,300
that I drew on
his contract with crayon?

777
00:52:57,380 --> 00:52:59,140
I will.

778
00:52:59,180 --> 00:53:01,180
And that I pulled
Dottie's hair so hard...

779
00:53:01,260 --> 00:53:03,260
that she cried.
Will he forget that?

780
00:53:03,340 --> 00:53:06,220
He'll forget.

781
00:53:06,300 --> 00:53:08,420
But make sure you don't.

782
00:53:20,220 --> 00:53:21,900
Hey, Alan...

783
00:53:23,500 --> 00:53:25,020
would you relax?

784
00:53:25,140 --> 00:53:27,980
There's nobody
following us, all right?

785
00:53:30,820 --> 00:53:32,740
This is a really big favor
I'm doing for you.

786
00:53:32,780 --> 00:53:36,260
You're lucky my cousin Karim
is working late tonight.

787
00:53:36,340 --> 00:53:37,620
Thank you.

788
00:53:39,300 --> 00:53:40,700
So, what's this guy's name?

789
00:53:40,780 --> 00:53:42,060
Louis Hunt.

790
00:53:42,140 --> 00:53:43,940
If he had an implant...

791
00:53:43,980 --> 00:53:46,820
there will be a record
of it in here.

792
00:53:52,420 --> 00:53:54,860
I could lose my job,
letting cutters in here.

793
00:53:54,940 --> 00:53:58,180
Come on, Karim.
Would I get you in trouble?

794
00:54:08,300 --> 00:54:10,540
They can track anyone
accessing data from a computer,

795
00:54:10,580 --> 00:54:13,980
so this is the best I can do.
Please hurry.

796
00:54:15,820 --> 00:54:18,620
Wait.

797
00:54:18,660 --> 00:54:19,940
These are genealogies.

798
00:54:20,020 --> 00:54:21,980
I don't know his family tree.
How do I use this?

799
00:54:22,060 --> 00:54:24,860
Hard copies are
sorted by series numbers...

800
00:54:24,980 --> 00:54:26,300
